```text

```
Comments associated with the post: 
Comment 1: You probably need to add an asterisk between the page-type class and the element, such as in the lines below. .path-mod-book covers the entire book page, but .book_content limits the scope to just the content of the book, and not the surrounding navigation. 
```text

```

```text
.path-mod-book * table.border-k td{ ... }
```
 .book_content * table.border-k td{ ... } If you use a theme such as Adaptable, you can place the CSS in the Site administration > Appearance > Themes > Adaptable > Custom CSS & JS page instead of mod/book/styles.css
Comment 2: Many thanks - unfortunately we can't change the theme on this site. This may be a basic question, but do you need to restart the server for the new .css to kick in as well?
Comment 3: No. but you probably need to purge the Themes cache on the Site administration > Development > Purge caches page.
Comment 4: Thank you - got this working with the overall SCSS in the theme, applied to the course ID. It was working all week. Now, we paste in the HTML (using the html "<>" in the editor. Unclick the tag and the preview looks perfect, with the css applied. Then click Save and the resulting page has the html tags displayed. Very odd. We did flush the cache, but I don't see how that would have caused this to change.
